we use recent results from the photometry and thermodynamics of radiation literatures to
develop an exact method for calculating 
the exergy of light and the exergetic efficiency of lamps.
The exact method 
(a)~is free of any assumptions for the value of the maximum luminous efficacy, 
(b)~uses the correct spectral exergy-to-energy ratio, and 
(c)~allows choices for the spectral luminous weighting function, 
which converts broad-spectrum electromagnetic radiation to light.
The exact method exposes shortcomings inherent to the conventional method and 
leads to a reasonable approximation of lamp exergetic efficiency, when needed.
To conclude, we provide three recommendations 
for societal exergy analysts:
(a)~use the exact method when a lamp's spectral power distribution is available, 
(b)~use the universal luminous weighting function, and
(c)~use the reasonable approximation to the exact method 
    when luminous efficacy is known
    but the spectral power distribution is unavailable.
